## Mustach.js

Example Working Locally:
html
Kopieren
Bearbeiten
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
  <title>Mustache Offline</title>
</head>
<body>

<div id="app"></div>

<script id="template" type="x-tmpl-mustache">
  <h1>Hello {{name}}</h1>
  <p>Your mood: {{mood}}</p>
</script>

<script src="js/mustache.min.js"></script>
<script>
  const template = document.getElementById('template').innerHTML;
  const data = { name: "Charlie", mood: "curious" };
  const output = Mustache.render(template, data);
  document.getElementById("app").innerHTML = output;
</script>

</body>
</html>
Let me know if you want to render lists, nested data, conditionals, or even partials with Mustache — it's super simple once you're set up.







Du:
does it need any rescources


ChatGPT:
Nope — Mustache.js doesn't need any extra resources to run. It's:

✅ Just a single JavaScript file (mustache.min.js)

✅ Has no dependencies (no jQuery, no Node, no CSS, nothing else)

✅ Works 100% offline in any modern browser

✅ Small (~5KB gzipped) and fast

Once you've included the script (either via CDN or local file), you're good to go — nothing else to install or load.

So your setup can be as simple as this:
html
Kopieren
Bearbeiten
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
  <title>Mustache Offline</title>
</head>
<body>

<div id="app"></div>

<script id="template" type="x-tmpl-mustache">
  <h1>Hello {{name}}</h1>
  <p>Today is {{day}}</p>
</script>

<!-- Local copy of Mustache.js -->
<script src="mustache.min.js"></script>
<script>
  const template = document.getElementById("template").innerHTML;
  const data = { name: "Ada", day: "Tuesday" };
  const rendered = Mustache.render(template, data);
  document.getElementById("app").innerHTML = rendered;
</script>

</body>
</html>
Let me know if you want a super lightweight setup to load templates from external .mustache files too — that's possible even without a server using fetch and file:/// paths, though with limitations depending on the browser.







Du:
